  "lesson_id": "lesson_auxiliary_nari",
  "lesson_title": "The Classical 'Is': The Copula なり (nari)",
  "lesson_summary": "In this lesson, we introduce the auxiliary verb 'nari', the classical equivalent of the Chinese '是' (shì). It functions as a logical anchor that identifies or describes the state of a noun.",
  "grammar_point": "auxiliary_nari",
  "grammar_explanation": {
    "concept": "The auxiliary 'nari' (なり) is the primary tool for assertion (断定). It functions like a mathematical equals sign (=), linking a subject to a predicate. In Chinese terms, it is the functional equivalent of '是'.",
    "formation": "Noun + なり (nari) / Noun + なる (naru)",
    "variations": [
      "なり (nari): Terminal form (Shuushikei) used to end a sentence.",
      "なる (naru): Attributive form (Rentaikei) used to modify a following noun (e.g., 'the X that is Y')."
    ],
    "common_confusions": [
      "Unlike Chinese '是', 'nari' comes at the end of the phrase (SOV logic).",
      "Do not confuse 'nari' with the particle 'ni' (location); 'nari' is a complete declaration of identity."
    ]
  },
  "teaching_sequence": [
    {
      "type": "introduction",
      "content": "Having mastered the 'tags' (particles) that define the roles of nouns, we now move to the 'glue' that defines existence and identity. In Classical Japanese, when you want to say 'A is B', you use the auxiliary <span class='highlight'>なり (nari)</span>. Think of this as the logical 'Return' statement in a function—it concludes the thought by declaring what the subject actually is."
    },
